{
  "doc_id": "40387",
  "text": "It is likely that there is not a simple, direct modulation of the effect by the opiate system, but rather an interaction with other systems. Support for this idea came from the finding that naltrindole infused into the nucleus accumbens of rats blocked the increase in extracellular dopamine elicited by ethanol or [D-Ala2]deltorphin II [CITATION_1] . Similarly, locally applied ethanol increased dopamine release, but not that of serotonin, in the nucleus accumbens, and that effect was reversed by naltrexone, suggesting the opiate system as a mediator of the reward of ethanol [CITATION_2] . Naloxone also inhibited the suppression of amplitude of excitatory postsynaptic potentials evoked by ethanol in the nucleus accumbens, indicating that ethanol might be acting by an opiate mechanism [CITATION_3] . Although there appears to be more evidence for that idea, there are still few clinical findings to indicate that it may be a useful tool in treatment of alcoholism.",
